About 20 smiling pupils entered the communal area with parcels of treats packed especially for each resident. Some residents were entertained in the communal room, while others remained in their homes and the pupils went to visit each there. Tea, coffee and treats were served before the music started playing. The first song was “The Macarena”, and some of the pupils and a few of the residents immediately began dancing around a large table in the communal area. ALSO READ: Thousands in fines issued in Kruger over December They all had fun, and some special bonds were formed between the children and the residents. A few of the pupils even called some of the residents their “new grandmother/grandfather”. The Nelspruit Care Buddies said they were very happy with how the outreach had turned out, and said it was clear that everyone enjoyed themselves. Do you have more information about the story? Please send us an email to editorial@lowvelder.co.za. For free breaking and community news, visit Lowvelder’s website: Lowvelder For more news and interesting articles, like Lowvelder on Facebook, follow us on Twitter or Instagram